1
00:00:01,651 --> 00:00:17,916
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto sambha-sambhodassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

2
00:00:17,936 --> 00:00:26,088
So, this moon, I thought I'd have a go at this Dullness and Lethargy.

3
00:00:28,263 --> 00:00:38,198
It used to be called sloth and torpor, which are, of course, moral view of them.

4
00:00:38,959 --> 00:00:44,307
And it's also listed in the seven deadly sins of the Christian tradition.

5
00:00:44,948 --> 00:00:45,728
You'll know them all.

6
00:00:45,848 --> 00:00:52,920
Pride, avarice, lust, envy, gluttony, anger and sloth.

7
00:00:53,996 --> 00:01:04,990
These days, we tend to use a gentler phenomenological, I'll say that again, phenomenological titles and call them how we feel them.

8
00:01:05,331 --> 00:01:10,378
So we feel them as dullness in the head and lethargy in the body.

9
00:01:11,299 --> 00:01:18,808
And of course, cognitive science always comes up with its own little definitions, arousal, dysregulation.

10
00:01:19,390 --> 00:01:20,831
So when you feel dull,

11
00:01:21,671 --> 00:01:28,361
When you feel very dull and lazy and all that, you can say, oh, this is just arousal dysregulation.

12
00:01:32,147 --> 00:01:38,457
So, yeah, tina mida, that's the word.

13
00:01:38,558 --> 00:01:49,114
So tina refers to this dullness in the head and the mida refers to this heaviness or physical torpor.

14
00:01:50,647 --> 00:01:53,750
Now, I don't think we put enough accent on this, you see.

15
00:01:54,290 --> 00:02:00,737
The other hindrances, everybody knows about sensual desires and ill will, anger and all that.

16
00:02:01,239 --> 00:02:06,765
And we know about restlessness and we know about remorse and guilt and shame and all that sort of stuff.

17
00:02:07,346 --> 00:02:09,348
And doubt often comes up for us.

18
00:02:10,609 --> 00:02:18,578
But I don't think we realize how pernicious dullness and lethargy is.

19
00:02:20,919 --> 00:02:24,164
So how does it come about, this doneness and lethargy?

20
00:02:25,306 --> 00:02:29,433
So consider certain situations.

21
00:02:31,698 --> 00:02:33,600
Sunday morning, yeah?

22
00:02:34,421 --> 00:02:38,830
And you wake up and you're nice and warm in bed and it's absolutely wonderful.

23
00:02:39,591 --> 00:02:44,598
And you think, I'll just roll over and roast the other side for a moment.

24
00:02:46,739 --> 00:02:53,387
So you don't need it, but it's just a lovely thing to disappear into this sweet oblivion.

25
00:02:54,427 --> 00:03:00,135
And especially when it's subliminal, you know, like you're not quite asleep, but you're not quite awake.

26
00:03:00,156 --> 00:03:01,576
And it just feels very lovely.

27
00:03:02,138 --> 00:03:04,941
Well, of course, that's really bad energy, right?

28
00:03:05,021 --> 00:03:09,127
I mean, everything we do creates physical or mental energy.

29
00:03:09,567 --> 00:03:13,472
So this energy now is one that pulls us down.

30
00:03:14,481 --> 00:03:23,977
And then there are occasions when we feel a bit bored, or we're a bit upset, or feel a bit depressed.

31
00:03:24,578 --> 00:03:26,020
We'll come to depression in a minute.

32
00:03:26,360 --> 00:03:34,373
Or we feel a bit depressed, and we think, oh, you know, and you sort of get on the sofa and disappear, or you throw yourself under the duvet.

33
00:03:35,156 --> 00:03:39,162
There's one way or another you sort of just get rid of yourself.

34
00:03:39,241 --> 00:03:41,586
It's a sort of soft suicide.

35
00:03:41,818 --> 00:04:08,872
right but it takes an effort you have to do it so you have to so there has to be this intention to disappear and and there's an energy that makes you do that and of course when it comes up in meditation or in ordinary daily life you just get this dullness in your head and this heaviness in the body so it's just a bad habit that's all now uh

36
00:04:09,426 --> 00:04:19,899
There was an Arahant in Burma called Sun Lung, and he attained full liberation at record Olympic speed.

37
00:04:20,600 --> 00:04:28,408
It seems he was a clerk in an office, and he met someone who taught him how to do breathing meditation.

38
00:04:28,668 --> 00:04:32,392
But what they taught him was this very heavy, fast breathing.

39
00:04:34,896 --> 00:04:38,319
You can get it on YouTube, S-U-N-L-U-N.

40
00:04:39,007 --> 00:04:42,233
And it was something like six months.

41
00:04:42,632 --> 00:04:44,675
He just did this practice.

42
00:04:44,716 --> 00:04:46,278
And within six months, he'd made it.

43
00:04:47,560 --> 00:04:50,184
And then began to teach the system.

44
00:04:50,264 --> 00:04:52,687
So, again, you can check it out on YouTube.

45
00:04:54,209 --> 00:04:59,538
And he was asked, why is it that people, you know, I mean, you did it in this express speed.

46
00:05:00,418 --> 00:05:01,600
How is it people don't?

47
00:05:01,680 --> 00:05:03,523
And he said, it's because they're lazy.

48
00:05:03,983 --> 00:05:04,264
Right.

49
00:05:04,925 --> 00:05:05,286
So.

50
00:05:05,637 --> 00:05:06,538
So there we are.

51
00:05:06,999 --> 00:05:09,202
That's coming from an Arahant.

52
00:05:14,372 --> 00:05:26,093
So the problem with that dullness and lethargy is that it then expresses itself as a sort of apathy, an unwillingness to do something.

53
00:05:26,392 --> 00:05:28,216
I can't be bothered.

54
00:05:29,057 --> 00:05:30,961
Boredom sinks in, you know.

55
00:05:30,980 --> 00:05:38,252
So it really has a long effect on us in terms of our attitude in daily life.

56
00:05:40,596 --> 00:05:43,622
You have to be careful not to confuse it with depression.

57
00:05:44,242 --> 00:05:47,930
I've got some stuff here which points out the difference.

58
00:05:49,151 --> 00:05:49,552
Hold on.

59
00:05:50,213 --> 00:05:51,134
Wait till I get to it.

60
00:05:55,790 --> 00:05:56,791
Here we are.

61
00:05:57,012 --> 00:06:08,656
So in meditation, the dullness or in ordinary daily life when you feel dull or you feel this heaviness in the body, it's normally just a state base.

62
00:06:09,137 --> 00:06:11,461
But if it's depression, it becomes a trait.

63
00:06:11,661 --> 00:06:12,182
It's with you.

64
00:06:12,403 --> 00:06:13,966
It's with you a lot of the time.

65
00:06:14,673 --> 00:06:20,944
And in the posture, it improves with lifting the energy.

66
00:06:20,985 --> 00:06:26,596
So if you feel drowsy in the posture, there are a few things you can do.

67
00:06:26,656 --> 00:06:37,677
You can open your eyes, let the light in, you can lift your body up, put more energy in it, and it normally will dissipate.

68
00:06:38,197 --> 00:06:48,391
The other thing, of course, is to sink into the feeling and just be with it and investigate its qualities, the softness of it, the tingliness of it.

69
00:06:48,872 --> 00:06:52,497
You'd be surprised how it feels when you drop into the body.

70
00:06:53,677 --> 00:07:04,153
And sometimes if you're dull in the head and you just wake up, as it were, and investigate this sort of porridge in the head, you'd be surprised.

71
00:07:04,173 --> 00:07:05,634
You wake up like a light bulb.

72
00:07:05,795 --> 00:07:07,156
It's quite remarkable.

73
00:07:10,040 --> 00:07:13,423
But if it's depression, it's a mood.

74
00:07:13,543 --> 00:07:15,365
It's very, you know, it just doesn't move.

75
00:07:15,386 --> 00:07:17,867
So you have to be careful not to confuse those two.

76
00:07:18,468 --> 00:07:25,396
And if you do think that you are depressed, then obviously you might need some help.

77
00:07:25,456 --> 00:07:28,158
Just zooming forward to the Buddha.

78
00:07:29,040 --> 00:07:33,785
So he had his early two disciples, Moggallana and Sariputta.

79
00:07:33,805 --> 00:07:34,706
They were Brahmins.

80
00:07:35,607 --> 00:07:39,911
And they became, of course, his two chief disciples.

81
00:07:40,329 --> 00:07:44,954
And Moggallana went to him for some advice about dullness and lethargy.

82
00:07:45,495 --> 00:07:47,956
And he gave these sorts of advice.

83
00:07:48,036 --> 00:07:55,504
He says, change the focus, put your attention on something which is going to raise your energy.

84
00:07:57,024 --> 00:07:59,608
In his terms, it could be reflecting on the Dharma.

85
00:08:01,088 --> 00:08:05,293
You can even do some chanting, just something to lift the energy.

86
00:08:06,194 --> 00:08:10,016
He also suggests that you pull your earlobes.

87
00:08:10,603 --> 00:08:12,146
So you can always try that.

88
00:08:12,487 --> 00:08:15,812
If you really press your fingers in, it really hurts.

89
00:08:16,572 --> 00:08:23,904
In the old days, that's what your parents used to get hold of, just to wake you up, you know.

90
00:08:25,266 --> 00:08:27,149
And then there's light, of course.

91
00:08:27,451 --> 00:08:30,394
I've mentioned opening the eyes and letting the light in.

92
00:08:31,377 --> 00:08:34,881
And then he says, oh, and walking meditation, of course.

93
00:08:34,981 --> 00:08:36,004
You can always do that.

94
00:08:36,759 --> 00:08:54,971
And also, just in order daily life, remember, after you've eaten, even if it's the right amount, if it's carbohydrates, the body does produce a chemical that makes you feel drowsy, wanting you to spend some time resting in order to digest and go through that whole process.

95
00:08:55,659 --> 00:09:00,913
But you have to be careful that you don't give in to the sleepiness of it.

96
00:09:01,374 --> 00:09:01,855
That's all.

97
00:09:02,395 --> 00:09:10,817
And if in fact you are overcome by sleepiness after you've eaten, then you might be eating too much.

98
00:09:13,379 --> 00:09:17,442
And then he says, when all that fails, he talks about mindful rest.

99
00:09:18,024 --> 00:09:18,423
All right.

100
00:09:18,825 --> 00:09:31,918
So to actually rest and just try a yoga thing of the yoga nidra, something like that, just to relax and, you know, not to actually lose consciousness.

101
00:09:36,121 --> 00:09:38,745
So let's go back a little bit.

102
00:09:42,572 --> 00:10:10,486
yeah so we've done that the causes yeah so just to run over those causes again I've got it listed here there's overeating sometimes oversleeping that's when you're indulging it's in blissful oblivion be careful of boredom that also makes you want to go to sleep so you know you have to lift up a bit of interest

103
00:10:11,480 --> 00:10:15,025
And physical exercise, don't forget physical exercise.

104
00:10:16,808 --> 00:10:23,299
It doesn't have to be much, but you've got to take care of the body in terms of its energy systems.

105
00:10:23,760 --> 00:10:32,095
So, you know, doing things like Tai Chi, yoga, but also some aerobic stuff like, you know, walking or cycling or something.

106
00:10:32,936 --> 00:10:36,542
All these add to a sort of general feeling of energy.

107
00:10:40,149 --> 00:10:48,183
Now, one thing you can do if you do feel sleepy is to, again, remind ourselves of the urgency of the situation.

108
00:10:48,784 --> 00:10:55,157
Every morning we wake up and I'm sure that we are absolutely sure that we will live the whole day.

109
00:10:55,658 --> 00:10:57,660
But there's nothing certain about that at all.

110
00:10:58,062 --> 00:11:03,532
And we can drop dead any time or we could be caught up in an accident or fall off a cliff.

111
00:11:03,572 --> 00:11:04,133
Who knows?

112
00:11:04,770 --> 00:11:30,846
like it's getting it's getting that feel that you know we're living on this knife edge and that brings a sense of urgency of wanting to really bring the practice into daily life sometimes you can bring inspiring teachers to my in teachings to mind so uh basically it's um it's

113
00:11:31,129 --> 00:11:32,932
It's a hindrance, right?

114
00:11:32,971 --> 00:11:33,913
It's one of the hindrances.

115
00:11:34,474 --> 00:11:38,278
It's a mental state that I think we have to take quite seriously.

116
00:11:38,979 --> 00:11:44,365
In my own practice, I've spent hours dealing with dullness and lethargy.

117
00:11:45,047 --> 00:11:47,730
And at one point, it used to last for 10 days.

118
00:11:48,331 --> 00:11:50,312
I used to just walk around in this fog.

119
00:11:51,053 --> 00:11:58,282
And there was a lovely occasion in a meditation room that I was staying in Malaysia at the time.

120
00:11:58,482 --> 00:12:00,445
I was working with Upandita.

121
00:12:00,897 --> 00:12:03,580
And everybody, of course, was getting up at half past three.

122
00:12:04,341 --> 00:12:11,710
And the diligent ones were, if they were falling asleep in the meditation, they were doing walking meditation at the back of the hall.

123
00:12:12,551 --> 00:12:15,315
And the lights were quite low, you know.

124
00:12:15,335 --> 00:12:17,136
And we're all sitting there.

125
00:12:17,157 --> 00:12:23,904
And there's this hell raising of a crash, you know, glass broken.

126
00:12:23,946 --> 00:12:24,907
It sounded terrible.

127
00:12:25,447 --> 00:12:29,993
And this poor, this poor meditator, he might have been a monk.

128
00:12:31,153 --> 00:12:34,158
or a nun walks straight into a glass picture.

129
00:12:34,639 --> 00:12:36,000
So that's how dull you can get.

130
00:12:37,503 --> 00:12:40,427
He wasn't hurt, but it was a funny occasion.

131
00:12:45,254 --> 00:12:53,206
Okay, I think we've covered basically all of it.

132
00:12:53,225 --> 00:12:57,852
There's always, let's have a look now, there's

133
00:13:00,009 --> 00:13:01,412
Oh, I've lost it.

134
00:13:01,432 --> 00:13:08,702
Come on, come on.

135
00:13:08,722 --> 00:13:09,724
Yeah, I think we've listed.

136
00:13:09,984 --> 00:13:13,269
So I think we've covered all those areas there.

137
00:13:13,428 --> 00:13:29,712
So I'd like to leave you with something I haven't said for a very long time, which is to recognize that we were most probably conceived on a bed and we probably were born on a bed.

138
00:13:30,418 --> 00:13:33,923
And we spend a third of our lives in bed.

139
00:13:33,964 --> 00:13:39,491
And when we're sick, we go to bed and we'll probably die in a bed.

140
00:13:40,092 --> 00:13:46,783
So it's good to remember that the bed is probably the most dangerous place on earth, right?

141
00:13:46,942 --> 00:13:48,284
And just stay with it.

142
00:13:48,785 --> 00:13:52,191
Every time you look at the bed, just think of it as the pit.

143
00:13:52,863 --> 00:13:56,407
So that you actually regulate how much you're falling asleep.

144
00:13:56,648 --> 00:14:00,972
Because any oversleep, that creates this bad energy, this downer.

145
00:14:03,135 --> 00:14:10,945
On a final note, there is a connection between restlessness and dullness and lethargy.

146
00:14:11,645 --> 00:14:17,232
Often in your meditation, you'll be quite restless and then suddenly find yourself dozing.

147
00:14:17,652 --> 00:14:25,072
And sometimes you're feeling very dull and unenergetic and suddenly you become restless.

148
00:14:25,552 --> 00:14:28,961
And as I experience it, it's the same energy.

149
00:14:28,982 --> 00:14:32,150
One of it's coming up and the other one's going down.

150
00:14:32,671 --> 00:14:43,865
So one trick when you are feeling dull is to start from the feet and just bring your attention up the body, feeling things, you know, it's an exploration.

151
00:14:44,625 --> 00:14:48,211
But don't go down, start again at the feet and just keep coming up.

152
00:14:48,230 --> 00:14:52,535
And that also, for me anyway, has an effect of, you know, lifting that energy.

153
00:14:54,575 --> 00:14:55,316
Very good.

154
00:14:55,436 --> 00:15:10,962
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and that by your diligent practice, never falling into the error of dullness and lethargy, you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

